<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">PFOF etc.</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic idea=C2=A0is that if a Robinhood cus=
tomer is buying stock, it is usually<em>=C2=A0</em>good to sell it to them.=
 In general, if you sell stocks, you will worry that the people=C2=A0buying=
 from you know something you don=E2=80=99t. They might know that, like, the=
 company is about to announce a merger or whatever, but realistically the=
=C2=A0<em>main=C2=A0</em>thing they might know is that they themselves plan=
 to buy more stock: If you sell them 100 shares of a stock at $10, and then=
 they buy 10,000 more shares, the price will go up and you will wish you ha=
d not sold to them at $10. If BlackRock Inc. is buying stock and you are se=
lling it to them, that is a real risk that you face; it is called =E2=80=9C=
adverse selection.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0But if a Robinhood customer buys 100 share=
s of stock from you, the chances=C2=A0that she=E2=80=99s buying 10,000 more=
 over the next two minutes are pretty slim. That is mostly not how Robinhoo=
d Markets Inc. customers behave. So selling stock to Robinhood customers wh=
o want to buy =E2=80=94=C2=A0or buying it from Robinhood customers who want=
 to sell =E2=80=94=C2=A0is a better and safer business than trading stock w=
ith BlackRock.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgroun=
d-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29993=
996.261528/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEt=
MDItMDUvcm9iaW5ob29kLWdhbWVzdG9wLXNhZ2EtcHJlc3N1cmVzLXBheW1lbnQtZm9yLW9yZGV=
yLWZsb3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIxNTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc2=
91cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMjE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB58c61b0e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talk</a> about <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29993996.261528/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMDcvdGhlLWlwby1tYXJrZXQt=
d2FzLXRvby1nb29kP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMTUyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWw=
mdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTIxNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZX=
lzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0d4bd9da" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  this</a> a lot around=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29993996.261528/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjUvc29t=
ZS1mcmVlLWJyb2tlcnMtYXJlLWNoZWFwZXItdGhhbi1vdGhlcnM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIxNTIyX01=
PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm=
09MjIxMjE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8382d42=
f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  here</a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Much of US equity market structure is driven b=
y this basic fact, that it is better to trade with retail customers than it=
 is to trade with professional investors. In general, when you trade on a p=
ublic stock exchange, you don=E2=80=99t know who=E2=80=99s on the other sid=
e. If there is an order to buy 100 shares, and you take the other side and =
sell 100 shares, you don=E2=80=99t know if you=E2=80=99re trading with a he=
dge fund or a retail investor; you don=E2=80=99t know if it=E2=80=99s the s=
tart of a flood of buy orders or just a random blip. But if you=C2=A0<em>co=
uld=C2=A0</em>know who was on the other side =E2=80=94=C2=A0if, say, you co=
uld know with certainty that everyone on the other side of your trades was =
a Robinhood customer =E2=80=94=C2=A0then that would be better. You could ma=
ke a lot more money trading only with Robinhood customers than you could tr=
ading with everyone.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so what you do is you go to Robinhood and =
say =E2=80=9Cwhen your customers give you orders to buy stock, don=E2=80=99=
t send those orders to the stock exchange, where they will be indistinguish=
able from orders from hedge funds and institutions =E2=80=94=C2=A0send them=
 to me.=E2=80=9D In return, you offer=C2=A0Robinhood=C2=A0three things:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You promise to give its customers bet=
ter=C2=A0<em>prices </em>than they=E2=80=99d get on the stock exchange. If =
some stock is for sale on the exchange for $10.01 per share, you=E2=80=99ll=
 sell it to Robinhood=E2=80=99s customers for $10.005 or something. This is=
 called =E2=80=9Cprice improvement,=E2=80=9D and Robinhood likes it because=
, as a broker, it has an obligation to get =E2=80=9Cbest execution=E2=80=9D=
 for its customers. Getting them a better price than they could get on the =
exchange seems like a good way to get best execution.=C2=A0In practice, you=
 won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>always=C2=A0</em>give Robinhood=E2=80=99s customers=
 price improvement. Sometimes it is=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>that good to tra=
de with Robinhood customers, for whatever reason =E2=80=94=C2=A0sometimes t=
hey are selling stock that you don=E2=80=99t want to buy =E2=80=94=C2=A0and=
 so you=E2=80=99ll just send their order to the exchange. But (1) you will =
always give Robinhood customers prices that are=C2=A0<em>at least as good=
=C2=A0</em>as they=E2=80=99d get on the exchange (since at worst you send t=
he order to the exchange), and (2)=C2=A0<em>most of the time=C2=A0</em>you =
will give them better prices. And Robinhood will keep track, and grade you =
on how often you give price improvement and how much, and this is a competi=
tive business and if you are not giving them enough price improvement they=
=E2=80=99ll send their orders to someone else.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">You=C2=A0<em>handle=C2=A0</em>the orders for Robinhood. If you=
 weren=E2=80=99t handling these orders, Robinhood would have to think hard =
thoughts about how to route its customers=E2=80=99 orders to get the best p=
ossible price. Should it send the order directly to the stock exchange? Whi=
ch one? (There are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/29993996.261528/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9ydWxlcy9zcm8uc2h0bWw/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB15997ee1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> more than a dozen</a>.) Should it send th=
e order to a broker=E2=80=99s dark pool? Should it split it up and send bit=
s to different venues? These are complicated questions that institutional b=
rokers have to think about as they try to get best execution for their cust=
omers. Robinhood doesn=E2=80=99t. Robinhood just sends the order to you, an=
d you decide whether to trade with it yourself or route it elsewhere, but y=
ou guarantee Robinhood a good price.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">Also you pay Robinhood money for sending you their orders. This is calle=
d =E2=80=9Cpayment for order flow,=E2=80=9D or PFOF. The intuition is that =
it is so profitable to trade with Robinhood customers that you can give the=
 customers price improvement, and you can give Robinhood a check, and yet i=
t is still a=C2=A0good business for you.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D=
"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-=
block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Meanwhile Robinhood uses these payments to subsidize its costs so=
 that it can offer its customers zero-commission trades, which the customer=
s seem to like. This encourages the customers to do more trades (they=E2=80=
=99re free!), which brings in more PFOF revenue for Robinhood.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The firms that=C2=A0do this business =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0who pay Robinhood for the right to trade with their orders =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0are often called =E2=80=9Cwholesalers,=E2=80=9D or=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cmark=
et makers,=E2=80=9D or occasionally =E2=80=9Cinternalizers,=E2=80=9D or, lo=
osely, =E2=80=9Chigh-frequency traders.=E2=80=9D Robinhood=E2=80=99s <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29993996.261528/aHR0cHM6=
Ly9jZG4ucm9iaW5ob29kLmNvbS9hc3NldHMvcm9iaW5ob29kL2xlZ2FsL1JIUyUyMFNFQyUyMFJ=
1bGUlMjA2MDYlMjBhbmQlMjA2MDclMjBEaXNjbG9zdXJlJTIwUTIlMjAyMDIxLnBkZg/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBb501fddb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> actual wholesalers</a> include=C2=A0Ci=
tadel Securities LLC, Virtu=C2=A0Americas LLC,=C2=A0Jane Street Capital and=
 G1 Execution Services LLC.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is hugely controversial for reasons we ha=
ve talked about a lot, and I won=E2=80=99t bore you again. (Basically: PFOF=
 feels like a bribe, zero-commission trading with PFOF encourages excessive=
 trading, it is bad for institutional investors =E2=80=94 like your mutual =
funds =E2=80=94=C2=A0to have retail orders executed away from the public ma=
rkets, people don=E2=80=99t like middlemen, etc.)=C2=A0But here I want to p=
oint out two specific controversial features that we have <em>not</em> talk=
ed about a lot because they are not usually the main things people get mad =
about.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First: The measurements of price improvement a=
re a little bit fuzzy. In general, retail brokers=C2=A0take a holistic view=
 of their wholesalers=E2=80=99 performance. They want to get price improvem=
ent on a large number of orders, and they want to get a large dollar amount=
 of price improvement. But they don=E2=80=99t =E2=80=94=C2=A0and, practical=
ly speaking, can=E2=80=99t =E2=80=94=C2=A0check whether they got the=C2=A0<=
em>most possible price improvement on every order</em>. In practice, someti=
mes the wholesaler does a trade that is very profitable for it: It would ha=
ve happily sold a stock at $10.003, but sells it at $10.007 instead, making=
 an extra $0.004. There is still price improvement =E2=80=94=C2=A0the publi=
c-market price is $10.01, say =E2=80=94=C2=A0but less than there could have=
 been. Other times, the wholesaler does a trade that is a loss leader: It s=
ells that stock at $10.00, when the =E2=80=9Cright=E2=80=9D price is $10.00=
3, and takes an $0.003 loss to provide good service for Robinhood. Over the=
 course of millions of trades in=C2=A0a month, the wholesaler has to (1) gi=
ve enough price improvement to make Robinhood happy and (2) make enough mon=
ey to make itself happy. But over the course of an individual trade that wo=
n=E2=80=99t always be true.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second: There is only a limited group of whole=
salers. There are some firms =E2=80=94=C2=A0Citadel Securities, Virtu, etc.=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0that are in this business, that have the relationships and =
algorithms and connections to operate as wholesalers to retail brokers. The=
y provide that complete package of services =E2=80=94=C2=A0reliable price i=
mprovement, professional routing, payment for order flow, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0to retail brokers; they compete to be good service providers to those br=
okers. A retail broker can send=C2=A0<em>every=C2=A0</em>trade to its whole=
saler, and the wholesaler will handle all of them at good prices.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But remember the basic point that it is, gener=
ally, good to trade with Robinhood orders. Lots of people =E2=80=94=C2=A0no=
t just professional wholesalers =E2=80=94=C2=A0would like to do it, at leas=
t on a part-time basis.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For instance, if you run a big mutual fund, yo=
u will not generally want to get into the business of making markets and pa=
ying for order flow. If Robinhood comes to you and says =E2=80=9Cour custom=
ers want to buy a lot of GameStop Corp. stock,=E2=80=9D and you don=E2=80=
=99t own any GameStop stock, you won=E2=80=99t sell them any. On the other =
hand, sometimes you will need to sell a million shares of some stock over t=
he course of a day, because your portfolio manager has decided she doesn=E2=
=80=99t like the stock anymore. What you would like to be able to do, in th=
at situation, is call up Robinhood that day and say =E2=80=9Chey, we=E2=80=
=99re selling XYZ stock, so if any of your customers want to buy it, don=E2=
=80=99t send their orders to Virtu, send them to us, and we=E2=80=99ll give=
 them a good price.=E2=80=9D You might trade at the midpoint price: If the =
public market price is $9.99 bid and $10.01 offered, you will get $9.99 per=
 share selling into the public markets, while Robinhood=E2=80=99s customers=
 might pay, say, $10.005 per share buying from a wholesaler (getting some p=
rice improvement over the public offer price). But if you cut out the middl=
eman, you could sell the stock to them for $10.00 even, and you=E2=80=99d b=
oth be better off.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In general this is not what happens: Mutual fu=
nds and other institutional investors don=E2=80=99t get to trade with a lot=
 of retail order flow; only the specific wholesalers with whom a specific b=
rokerage has negotiated arrangements do.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D=
"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-=
block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But sometimes those investors would=C2=A0<em>like=C2=A0</em>to tr=
ade with retail order flow =E2=80=94=C2=A0not as a business, just as a trad=
e =E2=80=94=C2=A0and they are sad that they can=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0</p>
